00:28:12.160 --> 00:28:14.830 align:middle line:90%
you can always pull it out.

00:28:14.830 --> 00:28:17.380 align:middle line:84%
Because delta 0 does
not depend on k anymore.

00:28:17.380 --> 00:28:21.920 align:middle line:90%


00:28:21.920 --> 00:28:22.910 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:28:22.910 --> 00:28:26.020 align:middle line:84%
So how do you like
this integral?

00:28:26.020 --> 00:28:27.640 align:middle line:90%
Can you do it?

00:28:27.640 --> 00:28:28.900 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: No, it diverges

00:28:28.900 --> 00:28:29.650 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Good.

00:28:29.650 --> 00:28:32.800 align:middle line:84%
So it's fruitless
to do this integral

00:28:32.800 --> 00:28:34.120 align:middle line:90%
because this is divergent.

00:28:34.120 --> 00:28:38.580 align:middle line:90%


00:28:38.580 --> 00:28:44.500 align:middle line:84%
And there's very good reason
for this divergence physically.

00:28:44.500 --> 00:28:47.530 align:middle line:84%
So this is just
the energy density.

00:28:47.530 --> 00:28:51.015 align:middle line:84%
So essentially, this is the
energy per unit volume--

00:28:51.015 --> 00:28:53.630 align:middle line:90%


00:28:53.630 --> 00:28:56.800 align:middle line:90%
say in some unit volume.

00:28:56.800 --> 00:28:58.920 align:middle line:84%
So let's imagine you
have a unit volume here.

00:28:58.920 --> 00:29:04.200 align:middle line:90%


00:29:04.200 --> 00:29:12.720 align:middle line:84%
Remember, this-- beside-- before
this, corresponding to you

00:29:12.720 --> 00:29:15.810 align:middle line:84%
take a discrete system with
some lattice spacing a,

00:29:15.810 --> 00:29:19.200 align:middle line:84%
and then you take the lattice,
and each lattice point,

00:29:19.200 --> 00:29:20.940 align:middle line:84%
you have a harmonic
oscillator, and then

00:29:20.940 --> 00:29:24.300 align:middle line:84%
you take a lattice
spacing-- a equal to 0.

00:29:24.300 --> 00:29:26.550 align:middle line:84%
So that means for
any unit volume, when

00:29:26.550 --> 00:29:30.090 align:middle line:84%
you take a equal to 0,
you have infinite number

00:29:30.090 --> 00:29:31.125 align:middle line:90%
of oscillators inside.

00:29:31.125 --> 00:29:33.810 align:middle line:90%


00:29:33.810 --> 00:29:35.475 align:middle line:84%
So essentially,
when you-- yeah, you

00:29:35.475 --> 00:29:39.180 align:middle line:84%
have the lattice of
oscillators at each point.

00:29:39.180 --> 00:29:41.310 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, I will not
try to draw it.

00:29:41.310 --> 00:29:45.390 align:middle line:84%
And then when you take a
to 0, you have any unit--

00:29:45.390 --> 00:29:49.680 align:middle line:84%
any volume unit, you will
have the number of oscillators

00:29:49.680 --> 00:29:53.430 align:middle line:84%
go to infinity, and that's
where this divergence come from.

00:29:53.430 --> 00:29:54.900 align:middle line:90%
It just come from--

00:29:54.900 --> 00:29:58.000 align:middle line:84%
in field theory, you have a
continuum degree of freedom.

00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:00.030 align:middle line:84%
So at each point, you
have a degree of freedom,

00:30:00.030 --> 00:30:02.670 align:middle line:84%
and within any volume,
then you definitely

00:30:02.670 --> 00:30:05.010 align:middle line:84%
have infinite number
of degrees of freedom.

00:30:05.010 --> 00:30:11.770 align:middle line:84%
so this is just from
continuum of freedom.

00:30:11.770 --> 00:30:15.430 align:middle line:84%
So this is the first
time you see a diverging

00:30:15.430 --> 00:30:18.160 align:middle line:84%
quantity in quantum
field theory,

00:30:18.160 --> 00:30:20.185 align:middle line:84%
but you will soon
find that this is--

00:30:20.185 --> 00:30:22.830 align:middle line:90%


00:30:22.830 --> 00:30:26.760 align:middle line:84%
soon, you find that
this is normal.

00:30:26.760 --> 00:30:28.080 align:middle line:90%
It will be a fact of life.

00:30:28.080 --> 00:30:31.410 align:middle line:84%
Just you will see
divergence very commonly--

00:30:31.410 --> 00:30:34.140 align:middle line:84%
and so-- because you have
continuum degrees of freedom.

00:30:34.140 --> 00:30:37.090 align:middle line:90%


00:30:37.090 --> 00:30:41.320 align:middle line:84%
So the whole thing about
quantum field theory

00:30:41.320 --> 00:30:45.580 align:middle line:84%
is to find a way to deal
with those divergences.

00:30:45.580 --> 00:30:49.840 align:middle line:84%
And one of the key differences
between quantum field theory

00:30:49.840 --> 00:30:52.970 align:middle line:84%
and just finite quantum
mechanics or finite number

00:30:52.970 --> 00:30:56.170 align:middle line:84%
degrees of freedom is
because of those divergences.

00:30:56.170 --> 00:30:58.120 align:middle line:84%
And the big part of
quantum field theory

00:30:58.120 --> 00:31:00.790 align:middle line:84%
is to understand how to
treat those divergences.

00:31:00.790 --> 00:31:04.180 align:middle line:84%
And they actually don't
affect your physics,

00:31:04.180 --> 00:31:08.830 align:middle line:84%
but you do have to develop
sometimes sophisticated tricks

00:31:08.830 --> 00:31:14.090 align:middle line:90%
to treat OK,

00:31:14.090 --> 00:31:14.590 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:31:14.590 --> 00:31:17.430 align:middle line:90%


00:31:17.430 --> 00:31:22.470 align:middle line:84%
And this infinite
answer is also closely

00:31:22.470 --> 00:31:26.670 align:middle line:84%
connected to a very famous
problem you may have heard.

00:31:26.670 --> 00:31:30.360 align:middle line:84%
It's called the cosmological
constant problem.

00:31:30.360 --> 00:31:34.740 align:middle line:84%
Because this tells you
that any quantum field

00:31:34.740 --> 00:31:40.480 align:middle line:84%
theory have an infinite,
say, 0 point energy.

00:31:40.480 --> 00:31:43.090 align:middle line:90%
And so you may say, OK--

00:31:43.090 --> 00:31:50.730 align:middle line:84%
so infinite-- whenever we
say something infinite,

00:31:50.730 --> 00:31:55.800 align:middle line:84%
there's one thing you
always do to treat it.

00:31:55.800 --> 00:31:57.620 align:middle line:84%
Can you guess what is
the thing you always

00:31:57.620 --> 00:31:59.150 align:middle line:90%
do when you see infinities?

00:31:59.150 --> 00:32:02.690 align:middle line:90%


00:32:02.690 --> 00:32:03.440 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:32:03.440 --> 00:32:05.550 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Just like
subtract infinity.

00:32:05.550 --> 00:32:07.600 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
that's one idea.

00:32:07.600 --> 00:32:10.560 align:middle line:84%
That's one idea, but to
subtract infinity is very hard.

00:32:10.560 --> 00:32:14.240 align:middle line:84%
In your calculus class,
when you subtract infinity

00:32:14.240 --> 00:32:16.680 align:middle line:84%
from infinity, you
can get infinity,

00:32:16.680 --> 00:32:19.580 align:middle line:90%
so you have to be very careful.

00:32:19.580 --> 00:32:20.270 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:32:20.270 --> 00:32:22.150 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: Just ignore the term.

00:32:22.150 --> 00:32:23.900 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: That's a
lot of very good idea.

00:32:23.900 --> 00:32:26.690 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:26.690 --> 00:32:28.220 align:middle line:90%
Indeed, that's what we often do.

00:32:28.220 --> 00:32:28.820 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:32:28.820 --> 00:32:30.980 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: Divide by.

00:32:30.980 --> 00:32:33.350 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: That's also-- indeed.

00:32:33.350 --> 00:32:39.220 align:middle line:84%
But to do all those things,
you have to do one thing first.

00:32:39.220 --> 00:32:40.090 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:32:40.090 --> 00:32:42.673 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: You might approximate
it, it's like 1 over the Planck

00:32:42.673 --> 00:32:43.300 align:middle line:90%
constant.

00:32:43.300 --> 00:32:45.180 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
it's also very close.

00:32:45.180 --> 00:32:46.434 align:middle line:90%
You need to do--

00:32:46.434 --> 00:32:47.267 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:47.267 --> 00:32:47.694 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Hmm?

00:32:47.694 --> 00:32:48.550 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:48.550 --> 00:32:49.592 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, exactly.

00:32:49.592 --> 00:32:52.900 align:middle line:84%
You need to find a way
to make it finite first,

00:32:52.900 --> 00:32:54.580 align:middle line:90%
and then you can subtract it.

00:32:54.580 --> 00:32:58.420 align:middle line:84%
And then you can-- yeah, just
like when you sum 1 plus 1/2

00:32:58.420 --> 00:33:00.740 align:middle line:90%
plus 1/3, et cetera.

00:33:00.740 --> 00:33:03.970 align:middle line:90%
You get an infinite series.

00:33:03.970 --> 00:33:06.290 align:middle line:84%
But if you want to estimate
the outcome-- yeah,

00:33:06.290 --> 00:33:07.090 align:middle line:90%
you get divergence.

00:33:07.090 --> 00:33:10.330 align:middle line:84%
But you always try to
cut it off the series,

00:33:10.330 --> 00:33:12.400 align:middle line:84%
and then approximate
definite answer.

00:33:12.400 --> 00:33:14.560 align:middle line:90%
And here is similar.

00:33:14.560 --> 00:33:19.060 align:middle line:84%
So here we always put
some momentum cut-off.

00:33:19.060 --> 00:33:22.840 align:middle line:84%
So imagine the
momentum is smaller

00:33:22.840 --> 00:33:25.930 align:middle line:84%
than some momentum--
say, some value lambda.

00:33:25.930 --> 00:33:27.610 align:middle line:84%
And lambda
corresponding to maybe

00:33:27.610 --> 00:33:30.520 align:middle line:84%
to the scale which this quantum
field is no longer apply,

00:33:30.520 --> 00:33:33.250 align:middle line:84%
because nobody told you
that this quantum field

00:33:33.250 --> 00:33:36.190 align:middle line:84%
theory should apply
at all length scales.

00:33:36.190 --> 00:33:39.880 align:middle line:84%
Because for example,
in this lattice model,

00:33:39.880 --> 00:33:41.815 align:middle line:84%
this scale will be 1
over the lattice spacing.

00:33:41.815 --> 00:33:45.440 align:middle line:90%


00:33:45.440 --> 00:33:49.910 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, so once you
cut it off, still you

00:33:49.910 --> 00:33:52.840 align:middle line:90%
get a pretty big number.

00:33:52.840 --> 00:33:57.040 align:middle line:84%
And you cannot ignore it because
this is a physical zero point

00:33:57.040 --> 00:33:57.730 align:middle line:90%
energy.

00:33:57.730 --> 00:34:00.280 align:middle line:84%
In principle, you
can measure it.

00:34:00.280 --> 00:34:03.980 align:middle line:84%
But in real life,
we don't see it.

00:34:03.980 --> 00:34:07.810 align:middle line:84%
So we have quantum fields
flying around all the time,

00:34:07.810 --> 00:34:10.580 align:middle line:84%
but we don't see this
big vacuum energy.

00:34:10.580 --> 00:34:13.900 align:middle line:84%
So this is called the
cosmological constant problem.

00:34:13.900 --> 00:34:18.429 align:middle line:84%
Actually, there was just
a colloquium last week

00:34:18.429 --> 00:34:21.310 align:middle line:84%
about this cosmological related
to this cosmological constant

00:34:21.310 --> 00:34:23.800 align:middle line:90%
problem.

