you get 0 assuming
we throw E0 away.

00:40:25.010 --> 00:40:31.070 align:middle line:90%
Say ignore E0 so far.

00:40:31.070 --> 00:40:33.980 align:middle line:84%
And then so for
the ground state--

00:40:33.980 --> 00:40:35.660 align:middle line:90%
and the p i acting on 0.

00:40:35.660 --> 00:40:37.430 align:middle line:90%
Of course, it's 0.

00:40:37.430 --> 00:40:40.590 align:middle line:84%
So you can see just
because this have ak here.

00:40:40.590 --> 00:40:42.560 align:middle line:90%
And so E also--

00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:45.242 align:middle line:84%
when we throw this away,
you have this --yeah.

00:40:45.242 --> 00:40:47.980 align:middle line:90%


00:40:47.980 --> 00:40:50.456 align:middle line:84%
And now, let's look
at the excited state.

00:40:50.456 --> 00:40:54.760 align:middle line:90%


00:40:54.760 --> 00:40:59.650 align:middle line:90%
So now to look at this state.

00:40:59.650 --> 00:41:02.320 align:middle line:90%
So H acting on k--

00:41:02.320 --> 00:41:05.650 align:middle line:84%
so this answer is obvious
because all different

00:41:05.650 --> 00:41:08.260 align:middle line:84%
oscillators, they are
independent of each other,

00:41:08.260 --> 00:41:11.770 align:middle line:90%
and this just gives you omega k.

00:41:11.770 --> 00:41:14.110 align:middle line:84%
We can just use our result
for harmonic oscillator.

00:41:14.110 --> 00:41:18.090 align:middle line:90%


00:41:18.090 --> 00:41:20.250 align:middle line:84%
And now, you can look
at the momentum--

00:41:20.250 --> 00:41:23.280 align:middle line:90%


00:41:23.280 --> 00:41:28.580 align:middle line:84%
so this is a spacetime momentum
operator acting on here.

00:41:28.580 --> 00:41:32.030 align:middle line:90%
And then it has k i.

00:41:32.030 --> 00:41:37.550 align:middle line:84%
If you look at this
expression, when you do the--

00:41:37.550 --> 00:41:40.730 align:middle line:90%
act this on that--

00:41:40.730 --> 00:41:43.520 align:middle line:90%


00:41:43.520 --> 00:41:48.470 align:middle line:84%
you act this on that,
and when you can just

00:41:48.470 --> 00:41:51.470 align:middle line:84%
use the standard trick
when you do the commutator.

00:41:51.470 --> 00:41:54.320 align:middle line:84%
And then the particular
k for this is chosen,

00:41:54.320 --> 00:41:57.775 align:middle line:84%
and then the eigenvalue will be
just given by that particular k

00:41:57.775 --> 00:41:58.700 align:middle line:90%
i.

00:41:58.700 --> 00:42:00.950 align:middle line:84%
So this is one step
of calculation there,

00:42:00.950 --> 00:42:03.470 align:middle line:90%
and you should do it yourself.

00:42:03.470 --> 00:42:06.830 align:middle line:90%
1-minute calculation.

00:42:06.830 --> 00:42:09.170 align:middle line:84%
This a delta function
will be generated,

00:42:09.170 --> 00:42:12.200 align:middle line:84%
and then that will get
rid of that integral,

00:42:12.200 --> 00:42:13.820 align:middle line:84%
and then you will
pick up this k i.

00:42:13.820 --> 00:42:18.220 align:middle line:90%


00:42:18.220 --> 00:42:20.440 align:middle line:90%
So now, this equation has very--

00:42:20.440 --> 00:42:24.790 align:middle line:84%
now has an obvious
physical interpretation.

00:42:24.790 --> 00:42:31.810 align:middle line:84%
So that means that this state
k has spacetime momentum.

00:42:31.810 --> 00:42:38.850 align:middle line:84%
So now, I write down a
four-momentum omega k n k.

00:42:38.850 --> 00:42:43.500 align:middle line:84%
So this is exactly the momentum
of a relativistic particle

00:42:43.500 --> 00:42:45.480 align:middle line:90%
on shell.

00:42:45.480 --> 00:42:49.200 align:middle line:90%
So this is of a relativistic--

00:42:49.200 --> 00:43:04.510 align:middle line:84%
so this is a momentum of
a relativistic particle,

00:43:04.510 --> 00:43:06.500 align:middle line:84%
because omega k is
equal to k squared

00:43:06.500 --> 00:43:09.440 align:middle line:90%
plus m square of mass m.

00:43:09.440 --> 00:43:14.190 align:middle line:90%


00:43:14.190 --> 00:43:17.560 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so this means
that the p squared.

00:43:17.560 --> 00:43:19.960 align:middle line:84%
So this is a four-vector
squared is equal to m--

00:43:19.960 --> 00:43:21.610 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so this
satisfies the p squared

00:43:21.610 --> 00:43:22.750 align:middle line:90%
equal to minus m square.

00:43:22.750 --> 00:43:27.560 align:middle line:90%


00:43:27.560 --> 00:43:29.570 align:middle line:90%
So we can just--

00:43:29.570 --> 00:43:31.550 align:middle line:84%
so it's very logical
just to interpret this

00:43:31.550 --> 00:43:37.240 align:middle line:84%
as a particle of mass m,
because we can just interpret it

00:43:37.240 --> 00:43:38.240 align:middle line:90%
as a particle of mass m.

00:43:38.240 --> 00:43:41.400 align:middle line:90%


00:43:41.400 --> 00:43:42.950 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:43:42.950 --> 00:43:46.080 align:middle line:90%
So now, let's look at this one.

00:43:46.080 --> 00:43:49.260 align:middle line:84%
So again, the calculation
is very simple.

00:43:49.260 --> 00:43:50.600 align:middle line:90%
So you find for that one--

00:43:50.600 --> 00:44:28.220 align:middle line:90%


00:44:28.220 --> 00:44:31.040 align:middle line:90%
so you find for that one--

00:44:31.040 --> 00:44:40.560 align:middle line:90%
for k1 k2, you find the energy--

00:44:40.560 --> 00:44:42.820 align:middle line:84%
energy just defined--
again, you find

00:44:42.820 --> 00:44:45.370 align:middle line:84%
that this is an energy
eigenstate of the H.

00:44:45.370 --> 00:44:49.450 align:middle line:84%
It's an eigenstate of H
with energy eigenvalue

00:44:49.450 --> 00:44:52.390 align:middle line:90%
omega k1 plus omega k2.

00:44:52.390 --> 00:44:55.480 align:middle line:90%


00:44:55.480 --> 00:45:00.700 align:middle line:84%
And it's a momentum eigenstate
of P i with an eigenvalue given

00:45:00.700 --> 00:45:02.860 align:middle line:90%
by k1 plus k2.

00:45:02.860 --> 00:45:09.480 align:middle line:90%


00:45:09.480 --> 00:45:27.954 align:middle line:84%
So E, k are
eigenvalues of H and P.

00:45:27.954 --> 00:45:28.920 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: Question.

00:45:28.920 --> 00:45:29.810 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah?

00:45:29.810 --> 00:45:31.890 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Yeah, so
could that mass be 0?

00:45:31.890 --> 00:45:34.830 align:middle line:90%


00:45:34.830 --> 00:45:38.540 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: So here-- so this
mass is not 0 because omega k

00:45:38.540 --> 00:45:40.970 align:middle line:90%
is defined to be this--

00:45:40.970 --> 00:45:44.970 align:middle line:84%
it's defined by my theory--
defined by my Lagrangian.

00:45:44.970 --> 00:45:48.990 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
parameter of your--

00:45:48.990 --> 00:45:50.670 align:middle line:90%
yeah, of your action.

00:45:50.670 --> 00:45:51.270 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:45:51.270 --> 00:45:54.720 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So I have a --
with the energy spectrum,

00:45:54.720 --> 00:45:55.650 align:middle line:90%
does the spacing--

00:45:55.650 --> 00:45:57.240 align:middle line:84%
does it happen
the same way where

00:45:57.240 --> 00:45:59.640 align:middle line:84%
the spacing gets smaller
as you go to higher

00:45:59.640 --> 00:46:00.750 align:middle line:90%
and higher energies or?

00:46:00.750 --> 00:46:03.780 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, for
here, it's uniform.

00:46:03.780 --> 00:46:06.390 align:middle line:84%
Here, just for each
k, it's uniform.

00:46:06.390 --> 00:46:08.140 align:middle line:84%
But of course, when
you add them together,

00:46:08.140 --> 00:46:10.590 align:middle line:84%
you get something
very complicated.

00:46:10.590 --> 00:46:12.675 align:middle line:84%
But for each k,
you just uniform.

00:46:12.675 --> 00:46:16.020 align:middle line:90%


00:46:16.020 --> 00:46:18.270 align:middle line:84%
So the very-- so
the most natural way

00:46:18.270 --> 00:46:29.310 align:middle line:84%
to interpret this is
just have two particles

00:46:29.310 --> 00:46:45.302 align:middle line:84%
of momentum of four momenta
omega k1 k1 and omega k2 k2.

00:46:45.302 --> 00:46:48.750 align:middle line:90%


00:46:48.750 --> 00:46:54.300 align:middle line:84%
And similarly, you can do
this for any state like this.

00:46:54.300 --> 00:46:56.910 align:middle line:90%


00:46:56.910 --> 00:47:11.400 align:middle line:84%
They are all eigenvectors
of H and P. So n k 1, n k 2,

00:47:11.400 --> 00:47:12.360 align:middle line:90%
you catch--

00:47:12.360 --> 00:47:13.320 align:middle line:90%
et cetera.

00:47:13.320 --> 00:47:21.105 align:middle line:84%
So this corresponding to n
k 1 particles of momentum.

00:47:21.105 --> 00:47:23.900 align:middle line:90%


00:47:23.900 --> 00:47:26.670 align:middle line:90%
They're all on shell--

00:47:26.670 --> 00:47:33.290 align:middle line:84%
on shell particle
of momentum k1 and n

00:47:33.290 --> 00:47:37.950 align:middle line:84%
k 2 has two particles
of momentum k2.

00:47:37.950 --> 00:47:41.490 align:middle line:90%


00:47:41.490 --> 00:47:44.190 align:middle line:90%
So this tells you one thing.

00:47:44.190 --> 00:47:48.225 align:middle line:84%
So now let me just
make some remarks.

00:47:48.225 --> 00:47:59.960 align:middle line:90%


00:47:59.960 --> 00:48:02.180 align:middle line:84%
Any questions on this
before I make my remarks?

00:48:02.180 --> 00:48:05.350 align:middle line:90%


00:48:05.350 --> 00:48:06.190 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:48:06.190 --> 00:48:08.410 align:middle line:84%
So the first point
is that now you

00:48:08.410 --> 00:48:12.430 align:middle line:84%
can see this can describe
any number of particles.

00:48:12.430 --> 00:48:21.150 align:middle line:90%


00:48:21.150 --> 00:48:23.010 align:middle line:84%
So mathematically,
in our description,

00:48:23.010 --> 00:48:25.830 align:middle line:90%
there are harmonic oscillators.

00:48:25.830 --> 00:48:27.838 align:middle line:84%
But each excitation of
the harmonic oscillator

00:48:27.838 --> 00:48:29.880 align:middle line:84%
is from the spacetime
point of view corresponding

00:48:29.880 --> 00:48:31.690 align:middle line:90%
to a particle.

00:48:31.690 --> 00:48:35.190 align:middle line:84%
So this is the beautiful
thing of this theory.

00:48:35.190 --> 00:48:40.730 align:middle line:90%


00:48:40.730 --> 00:48:44.810 align:middle line:90%
And then due to--

00:48:44.810 --> 00:48:49.190 align:middle line:84%
because of the commutation
relation, a k 1 dagger,

00:48:49.190 --> 00:48:53.440 align:middle line:84%
a k 2 dagger equal
to 0 for any k1 k2.

00:48:53.440 --> 00:48:55.990 align:middle line:90%


00:48:55.990 --> 00:48:57.550 align:middle line:90%
So you have full symmetry.

00:48:57.550 --> 00:48:59.260 align:middle line:84%
So when you construct
the state, you

00:48:59.260 --> 00:49:01.660 align:middle line:84%
can just commute
them as you want.

00:49:01.660 --> 00:49:03.640 align:middle line:90%
So that means they're--

00:49:03.640 --> 00:49:21.090 align:middle line:84%
so full symmetry in permuting
all these different particles

00:49:21.090 --> 00:49:22.215 align:middle line:90%
in the general state.

00:49:22.215 --> 00:49:27.840 align:middle line:90%


00:49:27.840 --> 00:49:30.560 align:middle line:84%
So this tells us
these are bosons.

00:49:30.560 --> 00:49:43.750 align:middle line:90%


00:49:43.750 --> 00:49:50.035 align:middle line:84%
And two is that all particles
have positive energy.

00:49:50.035 --> 00:49:58.010 align:middle line:90%


00:49:58.010 --> 00:50:07.510 align:middle line:84%
So even though that
E squared equal to k

00:50:07.510 --> 00:50:10.990 align:middle line:84%
squared plus m squared-- this
equation have two solutions--

00:50:10.990 --> 00:50:13.960 align:middle line:90%
plus minus omega k.

00:50:13.960 --> 00:50:16.120 align:middle line:84%
But when you look
at physical state--

00:50:16.120 --> 00:50:18.370 align:middle line:84%
when you look at your state
and look at the eigenvalue

00:50:18.370 --> 00:50:18.980 align:middle line:90%
of state--

00:50:18.980 --> 00:50:21.040 align:middle line:84%
so all particles have
physical energies,

00:50:21.040 --> 00:50:24.160 align:middle line:84%
so you don't have this negative
energy problem associated

00:50:24.160 --> 00:50:25.375 align:middle line:90%
with taking the square root.

00:50:25.375 --> 00:50:43.990 align:middle line:90%


00:50:43.990 --> 00:50:55.510 align:middle line:84%
Also you have total
energy of a state

00:50:55.510 --> 00:51:04.690 align:middle line:84%
is equal to sum of energies
of all the particles.

00:51:04.690 --> 00:51:11.890 align:middle line:90%


00:51:11.890 --> 00:51:15.250 align:middle line:84%
So this tells you there's no
interactions between them.

00:51:15.250 --> 00:51:19.390 align:middle line:84%
Because if you have potential
energies between particles,

00:51:19.390 --> 00:51:21.940 align:middle line:84%
and then that will
change the energy.

00:51:21.940 --> 00:51:24.190 align:middle line:84%
When you put the two
particles together,

00:51:24.190 --> 00:51:27.130 align:middle line:84%
will no longer be
the same over the sum

00:51:27.130 --> 00:51:30.280 align:middle line:84%
of the individual energy
for each particle.

00:51:30.280 --> 00:51:33.980 align:middle line:84%
And so that tells you
there's no interactions.

00:51:33.980 --> 00:51:38.186 align:middle line:84%
So this is a theory
of free particles.

00:51:38.186 --> 00:51:47.930 align:middle line:90%


00:51:47.930 --> 00:51:50.065 align:middle line:84%
Now, this is a good
starting point.

00:51:50.065 --> 00:51:53.050 align:middle line:90%


00:51:53.050 --> 00:51:54.580 align:middle line:90%
At least now, we have particles.

00:51:54.580 --> 00:52:05.170 align:middle line:90%


00:52:05.170 --> 00:52:07.030 align:middle line:90%
Questions on this?

00:52:07.030 --> 00:52:07.720 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:52:07.720 --> 00:52:12.640 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So
[INAUDIBLE] a k 1 let's

00:52:12.640 --> 00:52:14.710 align:middle line:84%
say, and you have a
particle with momentum k1

00:52:14.710 --> 00:52:17.950 align:middle line:84%
now, is there a way to change
this particle's momentum,

00:52:17.950 --> 00:52:20.530 align:middle line:84%
or if you apply again,
you-- like in this picture,

00:52:20.530 --> 00:52:23.285 align:middle line:84%
it's like you have another
particle momentum k1.

00:52:23.285 --> 00:52:24.910 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: No, there's
no way to change

00:52:24.910 --> 00:52:26.380 align:middle line:90%
the momentum of a particle.

00:52:26.380 --> 00:52:29.110 align:middle line:84%
So once you created
the particle,

00:52:29.110 --> 00:52:30.580 align:middle line:90%
it just goes straight.

00:52:30.580 --> 00:52:35.080 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, it just does
not change anymore.

00:52:35.080 --> 00:52:37.420 align:middle line:84%
Momentum for that
particle is conserved.

00:52:37.420 --> 00:52:39.160 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Is there--
if you wanted to--

00:52:39.160 --> 00:52:40.780 align:middle line:84%
if you wanted to
create a theory where

00:52:40.780 --> 00:52:43.300 align:middle line:84%
you can change the momentum,
is there a way, or is it just--

00:52:43.300 --> 00:52:44.870 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, there is a way.

00:52:44.870 --> 00:52:46.960 align:middle line:84%
So after dealing with
this free theory,

00:52:46.960 --> 00:52:50.500 align:middle line:84%
and then we will consider
the last simplest theory,

00:52:50.500 --> 00:52:52.360 align:middle line:84%
and then that will
introduce interactions.

00:52:52.360 --> 00:52:52.585 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: I see.

00:52:52.585 --> 00:52:52.660 align:middle line:90%
So--

00:52:52.660 --> 00:52:54.410 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: And when
you have interactions,

00:52:54.410 --> 00:52:56.620 align:middle line:84%
then the particle
momentum can change.

00:52:56.620 --> 00:52:57.120 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:52:57.120 --> 00:52:58.578 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So the
thing we're calling

00:52:58.578 --> 00:53:00.640 align:middle line:84%
particles are like
localized in momentum space,

00:53:00.640 --> 00:53:02.553 align:middle line:84%
but not at all in
position space.

00:53:02.553 --> 00:53:03.220 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Good.

00:53:03.220 --> 00:53:05.170 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, these are the momentum--

00:53:05.170 --> 00:53:09.220 align:middle line:84%
yeah, it's like the plane wave
in the non-relativistic-- yeah.

00:53:09.220 --> 00:53:11.713 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: And if you were to
try to localize it in position

00:53:11.713 --> 00:53:13.630 align:middle line:84%
space like a Gaussian
wave packet or something

00:53:13.630 --> 00:53:15.100 align:middle line:84%
kind of like that,
would you still

00:53:15.100 --> 00:53:16.780 align:middle line:84%
be able to commute
things and stuff?

00:53:16.780 --> 00:53:19.390 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, so
the commute things

00:53:19.390 --> 00:53:23.410 align:middle line:84%
don't change because
everything is built by a k,

00:53:23.410 --> 00:53:26.720 align:middle line:84%
and they always commute,
and so that won't change.

00:53:26.720 --> 00:53:28.750 align:middle line:84%
But indeed, we will talk
about the wave packet

00:53:28.750 --> 00:53:31.840 align:middle line:90%
to localize in space.

00:53:31.840 --> 00:53:35.090 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:53:35.090 --> 00:53:35.830 align:middle line:90%
OK, good.

00:53:35.830 --> 00:53:52.610 align:middle line:90%


00:53:52.610 --> 00:53:55.060 align:middle line:90%
So also-- so the last--

00:53:55.060 --> 00:54:01.150 align:middle line:84%
we will talk a little bit
about the technical point.

00:54:01.150 --> 00:54:04.900 align:middle line:90%


00:54:04.900 --> 00:54:09.130 align:middle line:84%
It's that so far, we haven't
talked about the normalization

00:54:09.130 --> 00:54:10.853 align:middle line:90%
of such a state.

00:54:10.853 --> 00:54:12.895 align:middle line:84%
So now, let's look at the
normalization of state.

00:54:12.895 --> 00:54:21.550 align:middle line:90%


00:54:21.550 --> 00:54:25.605 align:middle line:84%
So let's just look
at this state.

00:54:25.605 --> 00:54:26.980 align:middle line:84%
The single particle
state-- let's

00:54:26.980 --> 00:54:30.800 align:middle line:90%
look at this normalization.

00:54:30.800 --> 00:54:33.010 align:middle line:90%
So let's look at k with k prime.

00:54:33.010 --> 00:54:36.310 align:middle line:90%


00:54:36.310 --> 00:54:39.940 align:middle line:84%
So now, if you take the overlap
of this with the k prime,

00:54:39.940 --> 00:54:42.700 align:middle line:84%
and then you can reduce this
to the commutator of a k

00:54:42.700 --> 00:54:44.150 align:middle line:90%
and a k prime--

00:54:44.150 --> 00:54:46.120 align:middle line:90%
a k dagger and a k prime.

00:54:46.120 --> 00:54:50.380 align:middle line:90%
So you will get just this.

00:54:50.380 --> 00:54:54.560 align:middle line:84%
So again, this is a
five-second calculation.

00:54:54.560 --> 00:54:57.865 align:middle line:84%
So you find this if
you do the overlap.

00:54:57.865 --> 00:55:02.380 align:middle line:90%


00:55:02.380 --> 00:55:06.850 align:middle line:84%
But you already
did in your p set--

00:55:06.850 --> 00:55:09.310 align:middle line:84%
this thing is actually
not Lorentz invariant.

00:55:09.310 --> 00:55:11.150 align:middle line:90%
This is another good thing.

00:55:11.150 --> 00:55:16.150 align:middle line:84%
This is another good object
under Lorentz transformations.

00:55:16.150 --> 00:55:18.580 align:middle line:84%
But when we construct
state, we would

00:55:18.580 --> 00:55:21.400 align:middle line:84%
like to have our state to have
good properties under Lorentz

00:55:21.400 --> 00:55:23.260 align:middle line:90%
transformation.

00:55:23.260 --> 00:55:28.090 align:middle line:84%
So we will choose a slightly
different normalization.

00:55:28.090 --> 00:55:33.400 align:middle line:84%
