01:11:09.552 --> 01:11:11.850 align:middle line:84%
And so this is a fun
mathematical fact.

01:11:11.850 --> 01:11:16.450 align:middle line:90%


01:11:16.450 --> 01:11:17.820 align:middle line:90%
Good.

01:11:17.820 --> 01:11:18.810 align:middle line:90%
Questions on this?

01:11:18.810 --> 01:11:29.450 align:middle line:90%


01:11:29.450 --> 01:11:41.270 align:middle line:84%
So the last few minutes, we
talk about conserved charges.

01:11:41.270 --> 01:11:46.220 align:middle line:90%


01:11:46.220 --> 01:11:52.090 align:middle line:84%
Quantum-- the role
of conserved charges.

01:11:52.090 --> 01:11:58.480 align:middle line:90%


01:11:58.480 --> 01:12:05.410 align:middle line:84%
So classically, we
say if an action is

01:12:05.410 --> 01:12:07.450 align:middle line:90%
invariant under some symmetry--

01:12:07.450 --> 01:12:10.690 align:middle line:84%
some transformation-- some
continuous transformation,

01:12:10.690 --> 01:12:20.880 align:middle line:84%
say, of the infinitesimal
form, so the alpha are

01:12:20.880 --> 01:12:23.910 align:middle line:90%
the infinitesimal parameters.

01:12:23.910 --> 01:12:27.060 align:middle line:84%
So the alpha label
different transformations,

01:12:27.060 --> 01:12:28.950 align:middle line:90%
and a label different fields.

01:12:28.950 --> 01:12:31.140 align:middle line:84%
Alpha label different
transformations.

01:12:31.140 --> 01:12:35.820 align:middle line:84%
And then you will get
the conserved current J

01:12:35.820 --> 01:12:39.810 align:middle line:84%
mu labeled by this alpha,
so alpha label differently

01:12:39.810 --> 01:12:40.740 align:middle line:90%
for each.

01:12:40.740 --> 01:12:44.970 align:middle line:84%
So alpha label different
symmetries for each symmetry,

01:12:44.970 --> 01:12:47.760 align:middle line:84%
and then you have a
conserved current,

01:12:47.760 --> 01:12:51.345 align:middle line:84%
which is satisfy the
J mu alpha equal to 0.

01:12:51.345 --> 01:12:54.590 align:middle line:90%


01:12:54.590 --> 01:12:57.350 align:middle line:84%
The alpha equal to
1, 2, et cetera--

01:12:57.350 --> 01:12:58.940 align:middle line:90%
label different symmetries.

01:12:58.940 --> 01:13:06.800 align:middle line:90%


01:13:06.800 --> 01:13:10.760 align:middle line:84%
And then you can write
down your Noether current.

01:13:10.760 --> 01:13:13.490 align:middle line:84%
So we derive a general formula
for the Noether current

01:13:13.490 --> 01:13:16.475 align:middle line:84%
is given by the form,
say, partial L--

01:13:16.475 --> 01:13:19.250 align:middle line:90%


01:13:19.250 --> 01:13:23.446 align:middle line:90%
partial partial mu phi a.

01:13:23.446 --> 01:13:25.040 align:middle line:90%
And then f a alpha.

01:13:25.040 --> 01:13:26.790 align:middle line:84%
So this is essentially
the same as before.

01:13:26.790 --> 01:13:29.670 align:middle line:84%
Essentially, I just add the
index alpha now to label.

01:13:29.670 --> 01:13:32.070 align:middle line:84%
You can have more
than one symmetries.

01:13:32.070 --> 01:13:34.620 align:middle line:90%
And then minus k mu alpha.

01:13:34.620 --> 01:13:38.730 align:middle line:84%
So k mu alpha is
the derivative--

01:13:38.730 --> 01:13:43.410 align:middle line:84%
total derivative -- suppose
-- delta L is given by epsilon

01:13:43.410 --> 01:13:47.280 align:middle line:90%
alpha partial mu k mu alpha.

01:13:47.280 --> 01:13:51.070 align:middle line:84%
So the k mu alpha is the
total derivative corresponding

01:13:51.070 --> 01:13:53.280 align:middle line:90%
to that respect --

01:13:53.280 --> 01:13:57.270 align:middle line:84%
corresponding to
that transformation.

01:13:57.270 --> 01:14:00.420 align:middle line:84%
And then the q
alpha, that will be

01:14:00.420 --> 01:14:08.130 align:middle line:84%
the conserved charge for that
current, so zeroth component.

01:14:08.130 --> 01:14:09.810 align:middle line:90%
So this is the classical story.

01:14:09.810 --> 01:14:13.080 align:middle line:84%
Now, I'm using a little
bit more general notation

01:14:13.080 --> 01:14:15.730 align:middle line:90%
for each alpha.

01:14:15.730 --> 01:14:16.995 align:middle line:90%
So now, the key thing--

01:14:16.995 --> 01:14:21.115 align:middle line:90%


01:14:21.115 --> 01:14:23.240 align:middle line:84%
so now the key thing is
that at the quantum level--

01:14:23.240 --> 01:14:34.768 align:middle line:90%


01:14:34.768 --> 01:14:35.810 align:middle line:90%
so at the quantum level--

01:14:35.810 --> 01:14:43.910 align:middle line:90%


01:14:43.910 --> 01:14:45.500 align:middle line:84%
first, as we already
seen in the case

01:14:45.500 --> 01:14:48.320 align:middle line:84%
of the Hamiltonian and
the momentum operator,

01:14:48.320 --> 01:14:52.640 align:middle line:90%
so q alpha is time independent--

01:14:52.640 --> 01:14:54.170 align:middle line:90%
is a constant operator.

01:14:54.170 --> 01:15:00.260 align:middle line:90%


01:15:00.260 --> 01:15:03.050 align:middle line:84%
So this is the fact
that this is conserved.

01:15:03.050 --> 01:15:08.350 align:middle line:90%


01:15:08.350 --> 01:15:13.610 align:middle line:84%
And also another
important property of q

01:15:13.610 --> 01:15:19.520 align:middle line:84%
is that when you act
q alpha on your field,

01:15:19.520 --> 01:15:22.255 align:middle line:84%
if you look at the commutator
between this q alpha

01:15:22.255 --> 01:15:27.560 align:middle line:84%
on your field, it
actually generates

01:15:27.560 --> 01:15:30.760 align:middle line:90%
finite transformation.

01:15:30.760 --> 01:15:40.480 align:middle line:84%
So turns out-- yeah,
so if we have put

01:15:40.480 --> 01:15:42.325 align:middle line:84%
a parameter here--
epsilon alpha.

01:15:42.325 --> 01:15:45.190 align:middle line:90%


01:15:45.190 --> 01:15:47.770 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so it doesn't
matter for Q--

01:15:47.770 --> 01:15:50.680 align:middle line:90%
say, it's upstairs, downstairs.

01:15:50.680 --> 01:15:51.715 align:middle line:90%
And then you get--

01:15:51.715 --> 01:15:56.060 align:middle line:90%


01:15:56.060 --> 01:15:59.150 align:middle line:84%
so you just generate the
transformation for f--

01:15:59.150 --> 01:16:01.280 align:middle line:90%
for phi.

01:16:01.280 --> 01:16:03.120 align:middle line:90%
So this can be shown explicitly.

01:16:03.120 --> 01:16:05.900 align:middle line:90%


01:16:05.900 --> 01:16:08.520 align:middle line:90%
So you can show this explicitly.

01:16:08.520 --> 01:16:10.260 align:middle line:90%
We're running out of time now.

01:16:10.260 --> 01:16:14.540 align:middle line:84%
So you can show explicitly
just using this expression.

01:16:14.540 --> 01:16:20.310 align:middle line:84%
So let me just quickly
outline the way to do it.

01:16:20.310 --> 01:16:21.995 align:middle line:90%
So if you, say--

01:16:21.995 --> 01:16:26.510 align:middle line:90%


01:16:26.510 --> 01:16:31.956 align:middle line:84%
so let's look at the
zeroth component of this J.

01:16:31.956 --> 01:16:46.530 align:middle line:84%
So the zeroth component of
the J just equal to partial L,

01:16:46.530 --> 01:16:52.155 align:middle line:84%
partial, partial, 0
phi a and f a alpha.

01:16:52.155 --> 01:16:55.200 align:middle line:90%


01:16:55.200 --> 01:16:56.700 align:middle line:90%
So let's consider the--

01:16:56.700 --> 01:17:00.300 align:middle line:90%


01:17:00.300 --> 01:17:04.080 align:middle line:84%
yeah, I think today we will
not have time to finish anyway.

01:17:04.080 --> 01:17:08.640 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, let's just leave
this to the next time.

01:17:08.640 --> 01:17:11.640 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, let me just say
that the quantum level,

01:17:11.640 --> 01:17:15.160 align:middle line:84%
this will generate the
infinitesimal transformation.

01:17:15.160 --> 01:17:17.880 align:middle line:84%
And then you can
also exponentiate

01:17:17.880 --> 01:17:24.930 align:middle line:84%
